            "new_string": "## Task 6: Add Subresource Integrity (SRI) to Stripe JS\n\n> **Why this matters:** CSP whitelists `https://js.stripe.com` as a script source, but if Stripe's CDN were compromised, CSP would happily load the malicious script. SRI pins the exact hash of the expected file — a compromised CDN serving different content would be blocked by the browser. This is the strongest supply-chain defense for third-party payment scripts.\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `src/lib/stripe-loader.ts:36-37`\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Check if Stripe publishes SRI hashes**\n\nRun: `curl -sI https://js.stripe.com/v3/ | grep -i 'content-length\\|etag\\|cache-control'`\n\nAlso check Stripe's documentation for official SRI guidance. Note: Stripe's `v3/` endpoint serves a loader that dynamically fetches the actual SDK. Stripe has historically **not** published SRI hashes because `v3/` content changes without URL changes (it's a \"living\" endpoint). If this is still the case, SRI cannot be applied to `v3/` directly.\n\n**Alternative if SRI is not feasible:** Pin to a versioned Stripe URL if available (e.g., `v3/?advancedFraudSignals=false` or a versioned path). If neither is available, document why SRI was evaluated and rejected — this is still valuable for audit trails.\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: If SRI hash is available, add integrity attribute to script tag**\n\nIn `src/lib/stripe-loader.ts`, update the script injection (lines 36-37):\n\n```typescript\nconst script = document.createElement('script');\nscript.src = STRIPE_JS_URL;\nscript.async = true;\nscript.crossOrigin = 'anonymous';\n// SRI hash — regenerate if Stripe updates v3/\n// To regenerate: curl -s https://js.stripe.com/v3/ | openssl dgst -sha384 -binary | openssl base64 -A\nscript.integrity = 'sha384-HASH_VALUE_HERE';\nscript.onload = () => resolve();\nscript.onerror = () => reject(new Error('Failed to load Stripe.js'));\ndocument.head.appendChild(script);\n```\n\n**If SRI is not feasible** (Stripe's v3/ is a living endpoint), skip this step and instead add a code comment documenting the decision:\n\n```typescript\nconst script = document.createElement('script');\nscript.src = STRIPE_JS_URL;\nscript.async = true;\n// SRI not feasible: Stripe's v3/ is a living endpoint whose content changes\n// without URL changes. Stripe does not publish per-version SRI hashes.\n// Supply-chain protection relies on CSP script-src whitelist + Stripe's own CDN security.\nscript.onload = () => resolve();\nscript.onerror = () => reject(new Error('Failed to load Stripe.js'));\ndocument.head.appendChild(script);\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Build and verify**\n\nRun: `pnpm build`\nExpected: Build succeeds.\n\nIf SRI was added, verify in browser: checkout page should load Stripe Elements without console errors. If the SRI hash is wrong, the browser will block the script and log a clear error.\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add src/lib/stripe-loader.ts\ngit commit -m \"security: evaluate SRI for Stripe JS loader, document decision\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 7: Profile Hydration Before Optimizing\n\n> **Why this was deferred:** The original plan proposed switching `AddToCartButton` from `client:idle` to `client:visible`. A debate review found no profiling data to justify the change. `requestIdleCallback` already defers hydration to idle time (~50-100ms after paint), and above-fold cards get no benefit from `client:visible`. This task captures baseline metrics so a data-driven decision can be made.\n\n**Files:** None modified — this is a measurement task.\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Run Lighthouse on a representative menu page**\n\nStart the dev server and run Lighthouse against a menu page with many products:\n\nRun: `pnpm build && pnpm preview &`\nRun: `npx lighthouse http://localhost:4321/nl/ --output=json --output-path=./lighthouse-menu-baseline.json --chrome-flags=\"--headless\" --preset=perf`\n\nRecord these metrics:\n- **Total Blocking Time (TBT)**: target < 200ms\n- **Time to Interactive (TTI)**\n- **Interaction to Next Paint (INP)** if available\n- **Main thread breakdown**: how much time is spent on script evaluation vs layout vs paint\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Analyze hydration contribution to TBT**\n\nRun: `npx lighthouse http://localhost:4321/nl/ --output=html --output-path=./lighthouse-menu-baseline.html --chrome-flags=\"--headless\" --preset=perf`\n\nOpen the HTML report. Look at the \"Main Thread Work Breakdown\" and \"Script Evaluation\" sections. Identify:\n- How much of TBT comes from island hydration (Preact component mounting)\n- How much comes from network requests (`ensureCart`, `backgroundRefreshShipping`)\n- Whether the bottleneck is JS execution or network waterfall\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Decision gate**\n\nIf TBT > 200ms **and** script evaluation (not network) is the primary contributor:\n- Create a follow-up task to switch `AddToCartButton` and `ProductSuggestions` to `client:visible`\n- Include the baseline Lighthouse scores in the task description for before/after comparison\n\nIf TBT < 200ms **or** network is the primary bottleneck:\n- Document the finding: hydration is not the bottleneck, optimization deferred\n- Consider instead: lazy-loading SDK calls (defer `ensureCart` until user interaction)\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Commit profiling results**\n\n```bash\ngit add lighthouse-menu-baseline.json\ngit commit -m \"perf: capture baseline Lighthouse metrics for hydration profiling\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 8: Final Verification",
            "old_string": "## Task 6: Optimize Island Hydration Strategy\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `src/components/astro/ProductCard.astro:158-159`\n- Modify: `src/pages/[lang]/product/[slug].astro:325` (AddToCartButton)\n- Modify: `src/pages/[lang]/product/[slug].astro:334` (ProductSuggestions)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Change `AddToCartButton` in `ProductCard.astro` from `client:idle` to `client:visible`**\n\nIn `src/components/astro/ProductCard.astro`, line 158-159, change:\n\n```astro\n        <AddToCartButton\n          client:idle\n```\n\nto:\n\n```astro\n        <AddToCartButton\n          client:visible\n```\n\nThis is the highest-impact change — on a menu page with 40+ products, this defers hydration of below-the-fold product cards until they scroll into view.\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Change `ProductSuggestions` in product detail page from `client:idle` to `client:visible`**\n\nIn `src/pages/[lang]/product/[slug].astro`, line 334, change:\n\n```astro\n        <ProductSuggestions client:idle productId={String(product.id)} lang={lang} />\n```\n\nto:\n\n```astro\n        <ProductSuggestions client:visible productId={String(product.id)} lang={lang} />\n```\n\nProduct suggestions are always below the fold on product detail pages.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Build and verify bundle size**\n\nRun: `pnpm build && pnpm size:check`\nExpected: Build succeeds. Bundle size remains under 75 KB. The change doesn't affect bundle size (same JS, different load timing) but confirms nothing broke.\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run E2E tests to verify hydration still works**\n\nRun: `pnpm test:e2e`\nExpected: All E2E tests pass. Note: E2E tests use `waitForHydration()` which waits for `window.__MERCHANT__` — `client:visible` islands hydrate when scrolled into view, so tests that interact with `AddToCartButton` will trigger hydration via Playwright's scroll-to-element behavior.\n\nIf any E2E tests fail because `AddToCartButton` isn't hydrated when clicked:\n- The test helper `waitForHydration()` may need a small