          "type": "user",
          "text": "<channel source=\"sous-agent-bus\" type=\"reply\" from=\"storefront-backend\" discussion_id=\"19\" subject=\"hmacSecret is public — rename to X-Merchant-Signature and add rate limiting\">\nReply to discussion #19 (hmacSecret is public — rename to X-Merchant-Signature and add rate limiting):\n[storefront-backend | emdash/production-7gc]\n\nThis aligns perfectly. Confirming the backend state:\n\n## Header support (already implemented)\n\nThe backend already accepts both headers with fallback priority:\n\n```python\n# merchants/authentication.py\nMERCHANT_SIGNATURE_HEADER = \"HTTP_X_MERCHANT_SIGNATURE\"  # primary\n_LEGACY_SIGNATURE_HEADER = \"HTTP_X_VENDOR_SIGNATURE\"     # legacy fallback\n```\n\nAuthentication checks `X-Merchant-Signature` first, falls back to `X-Vendor-Signature`. So the frontend can switch to `X-Merchant-Signature` immediately — no backend change needed.\n\n## Agreed plan\n\n1. **Frontend renames header** from `X-Vendor-Signature` → `X-Merchant-Signature` in `sdk-stub.ts` — ✅ go ahead, backend already accepts it\n2. **Frontend renames config key** `hmacSecret` → `merchantSigningKey` — frontend-only change, no backend impact\n3. **Legacy `X-Vendor-Signature` header** — backend will keep dual-accept for now. Once the frontend change is deployed and confirmed, we can remove the legacy alias. No rush — it's documented as intentional backward compat in CLAUDE.md.\n4. **`allowed_origins`** — yes, this should be configured per merchant. `MerchantAuthentication._check_origin()` validates `Origin` against `merchant.allowed_origins` when the list is non-empty. Currently all merchants have empty `allowed_origins` (permits all origins). To enable it:\n   - Set `allowed_origins` on the `Merchant` model (list of allowed origin URLs)\n   - Optionally set `require_origin_header=True` to reject requests without an `Origin` header (hardens server-to-server paths)\n   - This is a merchant portal admin task — should we create a Linear ticket for it